{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15312"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15312"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.28,0.56,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66614"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52067"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21396"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66614"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of vague right upper quadrant discomfort. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She lives on a sheep farm in rural New South Wales and keeps several working dogs. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the right upper quadrant without guarding or rebound. Liver function tests are within normal limits. An ultrasound  examination is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Focal nodular hyperplasia","Simple hepatic cyst","Hydatid cyst","Hepatic adenoma","Pyogenic liver abscess"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound reveals a 8 cm well-defined cystic lesion in the right lobe of the liver with multiple internal septations and smaller cysts within it. This patient\u0027s presentation and the imaging findings are most consistent with hepatic hydatid disease, caused by infection with the tapeworm \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/em\u003E. The characteristic ultrasound appearance of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E includes well-defined cystic lesions with daughter cysts and internal septations. The patient\u0027s history of living on a sheep farm with working dogs is particularly relevant, as dogs are the definitive host of the parasite. Whilst at one time hydatid disease was a relatively common problem in the sheep farming areas of Australia, with improved hygiene and deworming of dogs, this condition is now seen infrequently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears as a solid, well-circumscribed mass with a central stellate scar and would not have the cystic appearance seen in this case. It is usually an incidental finding in young women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple hepatic cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are typically unilocular without internal septations or daughter cysts. They are usually asymptomatic and found incidentally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E are solid, well-defined tumours that typically occur in women taking oral contraceptives. They do not have a cystic appearance on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyogenic liver abscesses\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with fever, rigors, and marked right upper quadrant pain. Patients are usually systemically unwell with elevated inflammatory markers, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of hydatid disease typically involves albendazole therapy, often followed by surgical removal of the cyst. Care must be taken during surgery to prevent cyst rupture, which can cause anaphylaxis and spread of the infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydatid disease is caused by the tapeworm Echinococcus granulosus, with dogs being the definitive host.","Typical imaging findings of hepatic hydatid cysts include well-defined cystic lesions with daughter cysts and internal septations.","Risk factors include close contact with dogs and living in endemic areas such as the Mediterranean, Middle East, and rural Australia."],"references":["Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","Botezatu C, Mastalier B, Patrascu T. Hepatic hydatid cyst - diagnose and treatment algorithm. J Med Life. 2018 Jul-Sep;11(3):203-209. doi: 10.25122/jml-2018-0045. Erratum in: J Med Life. 2018 Oct-Dec;11(4):394. PMID: 30364592; PMCID: PMC6197524."]},"relationships":